ce that does not depend on climate variability."},"dropcap":false,"endmark":false,"lead":false},{"__typename":"EntryBodyParagraph","placement":{"id":"67wvYR","alignment":null},"__isEntryBodyComponent":"EntryBodyParagraph","contents":{"html":"We’ve got a problem because hydropower does not have the same variability as solar wind. So, if we get more solar and more wind, our system will have more variability. So, we need to get back up to that variability. And that’s where batteries are also important."},"dropcap":false,"endmark":false,"lead":false},{"__typename":"EntryBodyImage","placement":{"id":"OnEljn","alignment":"HANG_LEFT"},"__isEntryBodyComponent":"EntryBodyImage","contentWarning":"","image":{"url":"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/7B_rdcd01JGF26yKVIfUakTDfZs=/0x0:2700x1800/2700x1800/filters:focal(1350x900:1351x901)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/25408597/111023_Cachi_Dam_ICE_JCalma_0311.jpg","height":1800,"width":2700,"hideCredit":true,"caption":{"html":"\u003cem\u003eMarco Jiménez Chavez, an engineer who works on generation expansion planning at the state-run electricity utility Instituto Costarricense de Electricidad (ICE). \u003c/em\u003eThe Verge\u003cem\u003e spoke with Jiménez Chavez at the Cachí dam in Costa Rica.\u003c/em\u003e","plaintext":"Marco Jiménez Chavez, an engineer who works on generation expansion planning at the state-run electricity utility Instituto Costarricense de Electricidad (ICE). The Verge spoke with Jiménez Chavez at the Cachí dam in Costa Rica."},"credit":{"html":"Photo by Justine Calma / The Verge"},"asset":{"title":"A smiling man stands in front of electric power lines."}}},{"__typename":"EntryBodyParagraph","placement":{"id":"rmUpd0","alignment":null},"__isEntryBodyComponent":"EntryBodyParagraph","contents":{"html":"\u003cstrong\u003eWhat effects did El Niño and drought have in 2023?\u003c/strong\u003e"},"dropcap":false,"endmark":false,"lead":false},{"__typename":"EntryBodyParagraph","placement":{"id":"Kztqkn","alignm